• NASA-ISRO Synthetic Aperture Radar (NISAR) launched on July 30, 2025 aboard GSLV-F16 from Sriharikota into sun-synchronous orbit. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
• Equipped with dual-frequency radar (L-band by NASA, S-band by ISRO) to capture high-resolution data day or night, through all weather. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
• Capable of mapping Earth's land and ice every 12 days with centimeter precision—critical for disaster response, glacier monitoring and climate change insights. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
